# FromVecWithNulError in std::ffi::c\_str - Rust

```
pub struct FromVecWithNulError { /* private fields */ }
```

Expand description

An error indicating that a nul byte was not in the expected position.

The vector used to create a [`CString`](../struct.CString.html "struct std::ffi::CString") must have one and only one nul byte, positioned at the end.

This error is created by the [`CString::from_vec_with_nul`](about:blank/struct.CString.html#method.from_vec_with_nul "associated function std::ffi::CString::from_vec_with_nul") method. See its documentation for more.

## [Â§](#examples)Examples

```
use std::ffi::{CString, FromVecWithNulError};

let _: FromVecWithNulError = CString::from_vec_with_nul(b"f\0oo".to_vec()).unwrap_err();
```

##### [Â§](#examples-1)Examples

Basic usage:

```
use std::ffi::CString;

// Some invalid bytes in a vector
let bytes = b"f\0oo".to_vec();

let value = CString::from_vec_with_nul(bytes.clone());

assert_eq!(&bytes[..], value.unwrap_err().as_bytes());
```

1.58.0 Â· [source](https://doc.rust-lang.org/1.80.0/src/alloc/ffi/c_str.rs.html#215)

Returns the bytes that were attempted to convert to a [`CString`](../struct.CString.html "struct std::ffi::CString").

This method is carefully constructed to avoid allocation. It will consume the error, moving out the bytes, so that a copy of the bytes does not need to be made.
